    <note>Cai(1) Chong [12043] According to the Song shiyi, he was a lineage nephew of Jing [1649], but his generational name would make him a great grandnephew. The former makes more chronological sense, but this may be a senior branch of the lineage. Cong was fond of chatting about ghosts and spirits and when Jing's coalition (dang) recommended him to the court he arrived wearing the robes of a taoist priest. He rose to a postion as a drafting official concurrently reader in the imperial seminar. After the first time Jing left his position, he was attacked and lost his office. When Jing returned, Huizong warned him not to use Cong, but he did anyway. SHY:ZG, 42.38a-38b. CBD, 5, 3793.From Hartwell's ACTIVITY table:1115:  Promoted one grade as Fayunsi shuguan</note>
